[{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"CurrentModule = MinkowskiReduction","category":"page"},{"location":"#MinkowskiReduction","page":"Home","title":"MinkowskiReduction","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Modules = [MinkowskiReduction]","category":"page"},{"location":"#MinkowskiReduction.DeviousMat-Tuple{Any}","page":"Home","title":"MinkowskiReduction.DeviousMat","text":"DeviousMat(n)\n\nMake a unimodular 3x3 matrix that requires a large number of steps to reduce (See email from Rod Feb 1 2020)\n\nn dictates the size of the entries\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MinkowskiReduction.FibonacciMat-Tuple{Any}","page":"Home","title":"MinkowskiReduction.FibonacciMat","text":"FibonacciMat(k)\n\nGenerate a 2x2 matrix of the form [f2 f3; f1 f2] where f1, f2, f3 are consecutive Fibonacci-like numbers\n\nSee also: RandUnimodMat(n), FibonacciMat(n), DeviousMat(n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MinkowskiReduction.GaussReduce-Tuple{Any,Any}","page":"Home","title":"MinkowskiReduction.GaussReduce","text":"GaussReduce(U, V)\n\nReduce the basis vectors {U, V} to the shortest possible basis.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> GaussReduce([5 8], [8 13])\n([-1.0 0.0], [0.0 -1.0])\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MinkowskiReduction.RandLowerTri-Tuple{Any}","page":"Home","title":"MinkowskiReduction.RandLowerTri","text":"RandLowerTri(n)\n\nGenerate a random 2x2 matrix of the form [1 0; 0 Â±n].\n\nSee also: RandUnimodMat(n), FibonacciMat(n), DeviousMat(n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MinkowskiReduction.RandUnimodMat-Tuple{Any}","page":"Home","title":"MinkowskiReduction.RandUnimodMat","text":"RandUnimodMat(n)\n\nGenerate a random unimodular 2x2 matrix. n is a small integer (number of row and column operations).\n\nSee also: RandLowerTri(n), FibonacciMat(n), DeviousMat(n)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MinkowskiReduction.isMinkReduced-Tuple{Any,Any,Any}","page":"Home","title":"MinkowskiReduction.isMinkReduced","text":"isMinkReduced(U,V,W)\n\nCheck if the basis {U,V,W} is Minkoswki reduced.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MinkowskiReduction.minkReduce","page":"Home","title":"MinkowskiReduction.minkReduce","text":"minkReduce(U, V, W, debug=false)\n\nFind the shortest equivalent basis of that lattice formed by {U, V, W}\n\njulia> U = [1, 2, 3]; V = [-1, 2, 3]; W = [3, 0, 4]; minkReduce(U,V,W)\n([-2.0, 0.0, 0.0], [0.0, -2.0, 1.0], [-1.0, 2.0, 3.0])\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"function"},{"location":"#MinkowskiReduction.orthogonalityDefect-Tuple{Any,Any,Any}","page":"Home","title":"MinkowskiReduction.orthogonalityDefect","text":"orthogonalityDefect(a,b,c)\n\nCompute the orthogonality defect of three basis vectors.\n\nExamples\n\njulia> orthogonalityDefect([1,1,0],[1,0,1],[0,1,1])\n1.4142135623730954\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#MinkowskiReduction.shortenW_in_UVW-Tuple{Any,Any,Any}","page":"Home","title":"MinkowskiReduction.shortenW_in_UVW","text":"shortenW_in_UVW\n\nReduce vector W so that it is as close to the origin as possible.\n\nSubtract multiples of U and V from W. W will remain in an affine plane, which  is parallel to the U-V plane but which passes through the end of the W vector.  (See Lecture notes in computer science, ISSN 0302-974, ANTS - VI : algorithmic  number theory, 2004, vol. 3076, pp. 338-357 ISBN 3-540-22156-5)\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"}]
